Chapter 11: The Nine Situations	16
Chapter 12: Attack by Fire	17
Chapter 13: The Use of Spies	18

The Art of War

The Art of War is a Chinese military treatise written during the 6th century BC by Sun Tzu. Composed of 13 chapters, each of which is devoted to one aspect of warfare, it has long been praised as the classic work on military strategies and tactics of its time. As one of the oldest and most famous studies of strategy, it has had a huge influence on military planning, business tactics, and beyond.  First translated into a European language in 1782 by French Jesuit Jean Joseph Marie Amiot, it had  been credited with influencing Napoleon, the German General Staff, and even the planning of Operation Desert Storm. Leaders as diverse as
Mao Zedong, Vo Nguyen Giap, and General Douglas MacArthur have claimed to have drawn inspiration from the work

This summary is based on the translation of Lionel Giles. Dr. Giles wrote about his own translation: "It was not undertaken out of any inflated estimate of my own powers; but I could not help feeling that Sun Tzu deserved a better fate than had be fallen him, and I knew that, at any rate, I could hardly fail to improve on the work of my predecessors."

Chapter 1: Laying Plans
This chapter focuses on the planning stage of war.
Sun Tzu states the 5 factors that determine the outcome of the battle. These are:
1.	The Moral law
2.	Heaven
3.	Earth
4.	The Commander
5.	Method and discipline
These factors can be grouped as follows:
Heaven and Earth as the external factors, Moral Law and Method and Discipline as the internal factors, the Commander as the leader or manager.
Commander factor stands for the virtues of Wisdom, Sincerity, Benevolence, Courage, and Strictness. It symbolizes a war commander or any other leader or manager influencing and manipulating an organization.
External factors (Heaven and Earth) are the same for the two sides of the battle. As Sun Tzu said, the one who made more calculations regarding these factors, who adapt and take advantage of these factors, will be victorious.
In a modern interpretation of these factors Heaven is interpreted as the variable factors such as trends, weather, and current state of the economy. In making plans, the leader should consider the changing environment and be flexible to adapt and take advantage of the changes better than the opponents. Earth is interpreted as the constant factors such as geography, roads, laws and regulations. The plans should be in accordance with these factors. Together these two factors (Heaven and Earth) picture the current situation.
The internal factors are within the control of the leader. The Moral Law is what makes the leader and the followers believe what they do is right. According to Sun Tzu, if the leader has a right cause for fighting (and communicate this cause to the followers) the followers will follow the leader regardless of their lives, without loss of courage against danger.
Method and Discipline stands for the organization and means to achieve the goal. According to Sun Tzu, method and discipline is the organization of the army into subdivisions, appointing officers to ranks and building a supply network for the army and control of the army budget. We can see the same in modern organizations such as forming departments or teams, recruiting workers and appointing managers, the supply chain and cost accounting.
Since these five factors determine the winner and loser, every leader or manager should make plans and calculations regarding these factors. According to Sun Tzu, the one who makes more calculations before the battle will be victorious.
Sun Tzu says, to predict the winning side of a battle we should look at the following points:
1.	Which of the two sovereigns is influenced with the moral law (Moral Law)
2.	Which of the two generals has most ability (Commander)
3.	With whom lie the advantages derived from heaven and earth (Heaven and Earth)
4.	On which side is discipline most rigorously enforced (Method and Discipline)
5.	Which army is stronger (Commander, Method and Discipline, Moral Law)
6.	On which side are officials and men more highly trained (Commander, Method and Discipline)
7.	In which army is there a greater constancy both in reward and punishment. (Commander, Method and Discipline)
According to these points, the one with the right cause, better leader, taking advantage of the external factors and manipulating the internal ones in the right way will be victorious.
In order to plan and act right, the leader should know the position of the opponent. Obtaining inside information from the opponent is explained in the 13.th chapter, “the use of spies” but here in this chapter it is emphasized to prevent the opponent making a good plan, good preparations or a gainful move by giving false impression and misleading him.
Chapter 2: Waging War
The leader should know the negative effects of war before entering. War is costly. If you prolong the battle this will drain your resources and exhausts your men. This gives your opponents an advantage. Therefore victory should be gained quickly without having long battles.
In this chapter there are also recommendations about the reward system. Sun Tzu states that the soldiers (or workers) should share the common goal (in war, victory) in order to fight well. Also if they achieve something valuable they should be rewarded in order to keep encourage them to achieve more.
Chapter 3: Attack by Stratagem
In the art of war, the best achievement is breaking enemy’s resistance and gaining the victory without fighting. In the case of battlefield, conquering the enemy land without destroying it. There are two reasons for this; 1: war is costly and gain with minimum cost is more valuable. 2. Gaining a destroyed country isn’t a real victory since it has no use for the victorious side. Therefore the highest point of leadership is to disappoint enemy’s plans, next is to prevent facing the enemy, next attack the enemy, worst is to siege a walled city.
Sieging is not recommended because it usually takes much longer than a field battle to come to a result. And the result isn’t always guaranteed. Since it takes a long time, environmental factors can change and may turn against the attacker. The sieged city will close all connection to outside; therefore it will be much harder to get valuable information to consider during plan. As a modern business interpretation, entering a new market with barriers and starting a prolonged competition with other companies will likely result in defeat.
Sun Tzu suggests a rule for choosing the right strategy for attack (or not to attack):
•	If our forces are ten to the enemy’s one surround him
•	If five to one, attack him
•	If twice as numerous, divide our army in two
•	If equally matched, we can offer a battle
•	If slightly inferior in numbers, we can avoid the enemy
•	If quite unequal in every way, flee from him.
According to Sun Tzu there are 3 ways that a ruler can bring misfortune to his army:
1.	By commanding the army to advance or retreat, being ignorant of the fact that it cannot obey. This is called hobbling the army.
2.	By attempting to govern an army in the same way as he administers a kingdom, being ignorant of the conditions which obtain an army.
3.	By employing the officers of his army without discrimination, through ignorance of the military principle of adaptation to circumstances. This shakes the confidence of the soldiers.
According to these three rules, the army should be led by a military professional, not the ruler himself since ruling an empire is different than leading an army. Lack of knowledge in the art of war will cause the ruler to give orders which are impossible to obey, not to see and consider the conditions of the battlefield and appoint wrong men to critical positions. In the modern business world, owner of a company may be seen in the role of the ruler and the professional manager as the general. With the same three ways, the owner can bring misfortune to his own company. Like an army, if employees are restless and distrustful, company is open for external threats and anarchy.
Sun Tzu states the five essentials for victory:
1.	He will win who knows when to fight and when not to fight
2.	He will win who knows how to handle both superior and inferior forces
3.	He will win whose army is animated by the same spirit throughout all its ranks.
4.	He will win who, prepared himself, waits to take the enemy unprepared.
5.	He will win who has military capacity and is not interfered by the sovereign.
Since war is vital for the country the decision should be made after taking all factors into account. If there’s no gain in entering a battle, the battle should be avoided.
Not every leader has the chance of leading a superior force. The small army can also win. Also a large army can sometimes face an even larger army. In such cases the leader should be aware of the methods of leading both a superior and an inferior army in order to gain victory.
Communication and sharing the goal is essential for victory. In order to reach the goal of the organization, each member should share the urge to achieve it. In modern business world, corporate goals should be communicated to all employees and participation of them should be obtained.
The battle has two sides and all a leader can do to prepare his own army for the battle. Victory depends on the preparation of the other side. As Sun Tzu said, the winner prepares himself and waits for a chance to attack and gain victory.
In the introduction of Art of War, a scene from the life of Sun Tzu was told:
In order to test his warfare skills, King Wu asks Sun Tzu to prepare some of the girls from his harem as soldiers. Sun Tzu divides the girls into two groups and appoints one girl as the commander to each group. He trained the groups for basic right and left turns. When the girls ordered laughed and didn’t obey. Sun Tzu said “if the orders are not clear and cannot be understood, the general should be blamed. But if the orders are clear and still not obeyed then the officers are to blame” and wanted to behead the two girls in the role of group leaders. King Wu interrupts and wants Sun Tzu to spare the life of the two girls but Sun Tzu refuses. After the execution of two girls, two other girls were appointed as leaders but this time all the girls obeyed the orders. After this incident, Sun Tzu was appointed as general in the army.
Since ruling a country and leading an army is different, the general who is capable of leading the army should be left free in his job. In the modern business world, interference of company owners’ to the manager creates restlessness and reduces the performance of the manager. Often results as manager turnover.
Since strategy is important, this chapter was summarized by Sun Tzu himself at the end:
“If you know the enemy and know yourself, you need no fear the result of hundred battles. If you know yourself but not the enemy, for every victory gained you will also suffer a defeat. If you know neither the enemy nor yourself, you will succumb in every battle.”
Chapter 4: Tactical Dispositions
Sun Tzu emphasizes that a good fighter first secures himself, and then waits for a chance to defeat his enemy. This is because we can make preparations to secure ourselves, this is in our hands but we need a weak point to attack at the enemy’s side. Therefore protection can be guaranteed but victory cannot be.
In fact, standing on the defensive indicates insufficient strength, attacking excessive strength. A skillful general hides the strength of his army while standing on the defensive but when has the chance; he attacks like a flash and gains the victory.
The way to victory is:
1.	Measurement
2.	Estimation of quantity
3.	Calculation
4.	Balancing of chances
5.	Victory
All these are connected to other like a chain. Measurement is gathering data about the environment (Earth), Estimation of quantity is estimating the required resources, calculation is based on the amount of resources determined in Estimation of quantity, making many calculations, the leader takes every possible outcome into account and Balances the chances, after balancing the chances he chooses the best option that lead to victory.
Chapter 5: Energy
The control of a large force is the same principle as the control of a few men. Important point is to divide them into proper subdivisions and connect them with proper communication methods.
There are two methods in fighting; direct and indirect. In order to officially declare war, the general should attack directly but what gives the advantage is the indirect one. Since art of war is based on deceiving the enemy, indirect attack catches the enemy off-guard and gives much more damage. A skillful general uses these two methods in cycles and different combinations according to his calculations and strategy.
In order to deceit the enemy, the skillful general cloaks the true strength and order of his army and gives false impression of weakness and disorder. In some cases giving sacrifices as baits can be useful to keep the enemy busy with wrong places and advance him to our trap.
It is emphasized that a clever fighter takes advantage of the harmony of his men. In this regard Sun Tzu suggests the utilization of synergy instead of individual ability.
Chapter 6: Weak Points and Strong
As the result of being prepared for the enemy, the army which is already at the battlefield has the advantage. This is also similar with the market entry barriers in the modern business world.
The clever fighter does not let the game to be led by his opponent. Instead he imposes his will upon his enemy. He can either let enemy get closer to the trap or keep enemy distant according to the strategy. If the enemy is not responding his moves, he uses psychological tactics to prevent the enemy building and acting according to a strategy. After failing the enemy’s plans he attacks an unexpected point to gain the victory.
Against a skillful attacker, the enemy is never sure about what to defend; on the other hand the enemy is never sure about what to attack against a skillful defender.
If plans are prepared in secrecy and all conditions are ready for the plan to put into action, we can attack or outrun the enemy. We can force our enemy to act the way we want him to by giving baits.
The attack plans must be kept secret in order to confuse the enemy about what and when to defend. In such case, the enemy will be forced to defend several points causing him to divide his forces. Trying to secure different places, the enemy will leave weak point which gives us opportunity to attack.
The numerical advantage does not guarantee victory. By forcing the enemy to reveal his plans, leave a weak spot can bring victory to a smaller army.
One important point is not to repeat same tactics in different battles. Since secrecy and deceit is the key factors in victory, using the same tactics will be easy to defend for the enemy. Also since every battle has its own conditions, using generic tactics will not bring victory. Instead the general should consider the internal and external factors for that battle and come up with an unpredictable plan to deceit the enemy.
Conditions may change during the battle, therefore in order to gain victory the tactics should be changed according to the changing conditions. In the battlefield the one who can adapt and respond the changing conditions succeeds in winning.
Chapter 7: Maneuvering
Receiving the command from the sovereign and completing preparations for the battle, the general moves his army according to his plans and this tactical maneuvering is the most difficult part of war.
With right maneuvering the general can mislead his enemy and can reach the destination before the enemy army.
For the right execution of the maneuver, the army must be well organized, otherwise it will be impossible to move and maintain the order.
Another challenge in maneuvering is moving the heavy equipment quickly. A fully equipped army obviously cannot move as agile as a lightly equipped one but leaving equipment behind in order to gain speed and agility will weaken the army.
Longer walks than the capacity of the army are disadvantageous. Stronger men will reach the target but weaker ones will be lost on the way.
Maneuvering can be interpreted into modern business life as the changes. The manager makes changes in the way the company’s functions in order to gain advantage. During this change size of the company and weight of the change affects the company like Sun Tzu said about the army. Changing heavy equipment, building factories, changing the whole logistic system is much harder than making a small change. Therefore the changes should be extended through time in order not to exceed the changing capacity of the organization.
Before building alliances we must know the plans of our potential ally.
Before moving the army the general should be aware of the dangers and know the characteristics of the terrain on the way. In this regard having local guides is useful. If there’s no gain in moving the army, it’s the best not to move. The movements should be made according to the circumstances.
Making changes into new fields like new investments are risky for a company. Therefore all data must be collected and taken into consideration before making such decision. Like Sun Tzu said having a local guide is helpful. This local guide can be a consultant or someone having knowledge about the new investment.
In any possible action, the army should perform the best in order to gain advantage. Sun Tzu gives examples from the nature for the level of best performances such as rapid like the wind, compact like the forest, raiding like fire, immovable like a mountain, plans secret and impenetrable like the night, quick like a thunderbolt.
In order to move a large army in order, the general has to use gongs and drums, banners and flags. Sun Tzu emphasizes the importance of control and communication ways. In modern institutions reports will be the substitute for the banners giving the data about the position of the company. Gongs and drums are replaced by the modern communication technologies.
The art of warfare is:
•	The art of maneuvering
•	The art of handling large masses of men
•	The art of studying the moods
•	The art of retaining self-possession
•	The art of husbanding one’s strength
•	The art of studying circumstances
Therefore a skillful general should know where to move and where not to move the army. Should be capable of maintaining order of the whole army while maneuvering. Should understand the mood of both his men and the opponent and act in accordance with this mood. Should is calm and patient. Should is able to utilize the resources. Should be able to read the signs of the environment and the enemy and change plans accordingly.
Chapter 8: Variation in Tactics
Circumstances and environment limits the possibilities of the general.
There are roads which must not be followed, armies must not be attacked, towns which must not be besieged, positions must not be contested and commands of the sovereign which must not be obeyed.
Sun Tzu underlines the responsibility of the general for making the right choices that will be advantageous for his army. These choices include not moving, attacking, besieging and obeying the sovereign. Refusing to obey the orders of the sovereign is risky but if the general is completely sure of his judgment and success in the battlefield, he can take the risk and apply his own plans.
The modern interpretation for this can be rejecting unwise investment ideas of the company owners and avoiding entry to unfavorable markets and businesses.
The art of war teaches us to be prepared for enemy attack, to ensure our own safety, not relying on the chance of not being attacked.
There are five dangerous faults which affect a general:
1.	Recklessness: which leads to destruction
2.	Cowardice: which leads to capture
3.	A hasty tamper: which can be provoked by insults
4.	A delicacy of honor: which is sensitive to shame
5.	Over-solicitude for his men: which exposes him to worry and trouble.
To avoid these five faults, the general must make careful calculations of every detail, be brave in executing his plans, be calm and in control of himself, not to be too much importance to honor and not to be too soft and worried about his men.
Chapter 9: The Army on the March
When fighting, the general should not place his army in a disadvantageous position regarding the geographical obstacles. This can be done by knowing the terrain and effects on the battle. The general should also use this knowledge to gain advantage over the enemy.
This can be interpreted to modern business world like not entering a business with unavoidable difficulties and disadvantages. These disadvantages and difficulties can be because of geographical location and environment and also be caused by other unavoidable forces such as legal regulations.
All armies prefer high ground to low and sunny place to dark. And the general or manager should look for favorable conditions to execute his plans.
There are signs that reveal the intentions and feelings of both enemy and the general’s own men. If the enemy is near but remaining quiet, he’s relying on the natural strength of his position. When he keeps trying to provoke a battle, he’s worried about the possibility of the other side to advance. Rising of birds may be a sign of an ambush plan. Humble words and increased preparations are signs of an advance, violent language and pretending to attack are signs of retreat. When soldiers are leaning on their spears, this shows that they are hungry.
In modern world, a wise manager can look for signs from the opponents that reveal their plans. Also the wise manager can observe his own employees to get information about the real working conditions, level of morale etc.
In order to use punishment for discipline, the general should first gain the loyalty of his soldiers. Punishment is only useful on loyal soldiers. Therefore the manager should first gain the respect and loyalty of the employees then using punishments.
A general or a manager should have trust in his men/employees but always insist his orders to be obeyed.
Chapter 10: Terrain
Sun Tzu classifies the terrain in 6 groups:
1.	Accessible ground
2.	Entangling ground
3.	Temporizing ground
4.	Narrow passes
5.	Precipitous heights
6.	Positions of great distance from enemy
Ground which can be freely crossed by both sides is called accessible. For this kind of ground, the general should occupy the positions with advantage before the enemy. This can be matched with a new, untargeted market.
Ground which can be abandoned but is hard to re-occupy is called entangling. An attack from this kind of ground may be disadvantageous because in need of retreat it will be hard to cross an entangling ground. This can be matched with a market with exit barriers.
Ground with the position that neither side will gain by making the first move is called temporizing ground. In such ground its better not to be tricked and pulled into battle by baits. On the other hand forcing the enemy to advance first will give us an advantage.
In case of the narrow passes, if we occupy them with strong forces, this will be advantage for us, but it’s risky to follow an enemy escaping through a narrow pass. If the pass is heavily garrisoned by the enemy, best is to stay out.
In case of precipitous heights it’s advised to occupy advantageous locations before the enemy and not to follow an enemy which has already occupied these locations.
If there’s a great distance between two armies, it’s not hard and not wise to start a fight. In such cases the army should be advanced near the enemy, will be tired and maybe exposed.
There are 6 faults that the general is responsible of:
1.	Flight
2.	Insubordination
3.	Collapse
4.	Ruin
5.	Disorganization
6.	Rout
If two armies with an enormous difference in size meet, the result is the flight of the smaller one.
If the soldiers are strong but the officers are weak, the result is insubordination. In this case the soldiers will not respect and obey the officers. In modern business life a manager lacking the expert power will have problems in establishing his authority on his subordinates.
If the officers are strong but the common soldiers are weak, the result is collapse. Since the victory will be gained through synergy, having a talented leader is not enough. There should be strong men under him to achieve the goals.
If the higher officers have problems with the leader and insubordinate, they will not wait for orders or obey given ones. In this case the officers will act on their own account and the result is ruin. Appointing someone as the top manager may cause displeasure or envy on others. This will have negative effect on the harmony of the top management and should be avoided.
If the general is not capable of leading, officers will be disobedient. The result is disorganization. In order to gain victory, all ranks should be occupied by talented members of organization. Authority and discipline must be established before entering any battle.
When a general is unable to estimate the strength of the enemy and attacks a strong army with a weak one, the result is rout.
The geographical conditions are the most important factors in battle. The general will make his calculations, estimates the power of enemy and prepares tactics to bring him victory.
Regarding the calculations, if the result will be victory then the general must fight even if the sovereign orders to retreat. The general must not fight if the calculations show a defeat even if the sovereign orders to attack.
Sun Tzu recommends the leaders to regard their soldiers as their own children to make them also be emotionally connected to the leader and follow him to death. But if the leader is unable to establish his authority, these soldiers will be like spoiled children and are useless.
Conditions of our army, enemy’s army and natural environment are three pillars of victory. A general should know each of them to be victorious. Sun Tzu said, “if you know the enemy and know yourself, your victory will not stand in doubt. If you know Heaven and know Earth, you may make your victory complete”.
In modern business life, the manager should know the capabilities of his company and also the competitors’. If he also knows the external factors that affect the market, his success is guaranteed.
Chapter 11: The Nine Situations
Sun Tzu classified the battlefield according to location in 9 groups:
1.	Dispersive ground: when a chieftain is fighting in his own territory, it is dispersive ground. It is not recommended to fight in dispersive ground.
2.	Facile ground: when he is a little inside the hostile territory, it is facile ground.It’s not recommended on facile ground to stop and fight. This slows down your speed into the country.
3.	Contentious ground: the ground which gives a great advantage to holder is contentious ground. It’s not recommended to attack from contentious ground since holding it is more advantageous.
4.	Open ground: the ground on which each side has the freedom to move is open ground. On this ground it’s not recommended to block enemy’s way, since the ground is easy in every side, blockage is meaningless.
5.	Ground of intersecting highways: the ground which forms the key to three neighboring states is ground of intersecting highways. The one who controls this also controls the others. On this kind of ground it’s recommended to make alliances with neighboring states.
6.	Serious ground: If the army penetrates deep into the hostile country leaving fortified cities behind, it is serious ground. In such ground it is recommended to gather the plundered resources from the before taken towns to use in the future battles ahead.
7.	Difficult ground: If the enemy territory is geographically challenging, it is called difficult ground. In this ground it’s not recommended to stop and camp. The army should keep marching to get out as soon as possible.
8.	Hemmed-in ground: the ground which is reached through narrow paths and hard to retreat is hemmed-in ground. This kind of ground we can use to camp and make our plans.
9.	Desperate ground: the ground on which we can be saved by destruction by fighting without delay is desperate ground. There’s no choice in desperate ground other than fighting.
The skillful general knows point in the enemy army which he should attach. Attacking to this point he splits the enemy army, prevent the parts help each other. A skillful general is capable of causing disorder in the enemy army. The skillful general only moves his army if there’s gain in moving. If not, he keeps still.
In desperate situations, soldiers fight without fear. If there’s no place to retreat, soldier will do his best to survive. In such situations soldiers are perfectly loyal and trustworthy.
Omens and other superstitious thoughts discourage the army. The general should avoid them have effect on the soldiers. Until death itself comes, there’s nothing to be afraid of.
The army led by a skillful tactician looks like a snake. If attacked at the head, it will attack with its tail. If attacked at the tail, the head will retaliate. If attacked in the middle, both head and tail will respond.
Even enemies can be allies in some conditions. It’s the talent to bring them together.
Chapter 12: Attack by Fire
According to Sun Tzu there are five ways of attacking by fire:
1.	Burn soldiers in their camp
2.	Burn stores
3.	Burn baggage trains
4.	Burn arsenals and magazines
5.	Throw fire at the enemy.
All of them except the last one are indirect war. In the first four ones attacking by fire weakens the enemy, decreases their supply and breaks his courage. The last one is the usage of fire as a weapon.
In use of fire, the season and wind should be taken into consideration. A dry summer is the ideal season.
In attacking by fire, there are five possible developments:
1.	When fire breaks out inside the enemy camp, also attack with fire from outside.
2.	If there’s an outbreak of fire but enemy’s soldiers remain quit, do not attack. Let the fire do more damage before noticed.
3.	When the fire reaches its limit, attack the enemy camp as possible. If it is not practical, stay where you are.
4.	If it is possible to attack with fire from outside, do not wait for the inside fire, attack when possible.
5.	When you start a fire keep the wind on your back. Do not get caught in the fire.
When attacking by fire, stealing some of the water from enemy is useful. If you steal all the water the enemy will understand that fire is coming and gets prepared for it.
It’s repeated several times through the book: “move if there’s gain, if not, stay where you are”.
Chapter 13: The Use of Spies
Since war is costly and may last for a long time, the victory gained after such loss is not considered as victory.
The wise sovereign and good general strikes and conquers, achieves things beyond the reach of ordinary men, is done by foreknowledge. Foreknowledge cannot be obtained from spirits, from experience and it cannot be calculated. Valuable information about the enemy is obtained from other men (spies).
There are five classes of spies:
1.	Local spies are the inhabitants of a district
2.	Inward spies are officials of the enemy
3.	Converted spies are enemy’s spies getting caught and used for our own purposes
4.	Having doomed spies is doing things openly for purposes of deception. (by reporting a doomed spy to the enemy, makes our other spy trustworthy for the him)
5.	Surviving spies are those who bring back news form the enemy’s camp.
Deploying all five kinds of spy is called “divine manipulation of the threads” and it’s a very valuable advantage.
Sun Tzu recommends the usage of spies also in businesses other than war.
There are also spies in modern business life but there are other sources which provide inside information from the competitor company such as job applicants working at the competitors. Since inside information holds essential part in our attack and defense plans, usage of spies adds great power to an army and a company.